WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:08.900
Look at this evidence bench for a second. Pencil. Water.
Spoon. Salt. A copper coin. Even the air you just breathed
out.

2
00:00:08.900 --> 00:00:17.045
They could not look more different. One writes, one flows,
one clinks, and one sits there pretending to be a tiny
shiny medal.

3
00:00:17.045 --> 00:00:24.850
And the salt? Stir it into water and it seems to vanish.
It has not vanished. It is hiding in plain sight.

4
00:00:24.850 --> 00:00:33.928
Chemistry starts with one brilliant idea: none of this is
magic. It is all built from pieces so small your eyes will
never win that argument.

5
00:00:33.928 --> 00:00:42.804
Chemists use models because we cannot directly see that
tiny world. A model is not a photograph. It is a thinking
tool, like a map.

6
00:00:42.804 --> 00:00:54.945
A useful model does not show every detail. It shows the
detail we need for the question. If the question is about
sorting matter, the model should show what particles are

7
00:00:54.945 --> 00:01:01.241
One important tiny unit is an atom. Atoms are the basic
characters in the chemistry alphabet.

8
00:01:01.241 --> 00:01:11.344
An element is matter made from one type of atom. Pure gold
has gold atoms. Pure copper has copper atoms. The graphite
in a pencil contains carbon atoms.

9
00:01:11.344 --> 00:01:26.693
Atoms can join together as units called molecules. Oxygen
gas is a useful trick case: it is a molecule because
oxygen atoms are joined in pairs, and it is still an

10
00:01:26.693 --> 00:01:39.882
When different elements are chemically joined, we call the
substance a compound. Water is a compound. Table salt is a
compound too, but it is not a neat little salt molecule;

11
00:01:39.882 --> 00:01:52.560
A mixture is different. In a mixture, substances are
together, but they have not been rebuilt into one new
substance. Air is a mixture. Salt water is a mixture.

12
00:01:52.560 --> 00:02:06.586
Now sort three examples. Copper coin: one type of atom, so
element. Water: hydrogen and oxygen chemically joined, so
compound. Salt water: water and salt together, so mixture.

13
00:02:06.586 --> 00:02:17.916
The words can overlap in careful ways. Water is a molecule
and a compound. Oxygen gas is a molecule and an element.
That is not a mistake; the words answer different

14
00:02:17.916 --> 00:02:31.809
Molecule asks: are atoms joined as a unit? Element asks:
is there only one type of atom? Compound asks: are
different elements chemically joined? Mixture asks: are

15
00:02:31.809 --> 00:02:49.609
Here is a tiny exam-style trap. A thing can fit more than
one word. Oxygen gas is an element and a molecule. Water
is a molecule and a compound. But air is not a compound,

16
00:02:49.609 --> 00:03:01.795
Another trap: do not call every tiny dot an atom. Salt
water has water molecules and dissolved salt particles.
The model is allowed to be simple, but our words still

17
00:03:01.795 --> 00:03:08.565
So here is the first chemist move. Ask: what is it made
from, and are the pieces joined or just together?

18
00:03:08.565 --> 00:03:13.755
Today we start the code: atoms, elements, molecules,
compounds, and mixtures.
